SIMPLE: imaginative
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imaginative
<hw>Im*ag"i*na*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>imaginatif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Proceeding from, and
characterized by, the imagination, generally in the highest sense of the
word.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In all the higher departments of <qex>imaginative</qex> art,
nature still constitutes an important element.</q>
<rj><qau>Mure.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Given to imagining; full of images, fancies, etc.;
having a quick imagination; conceptive; creative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Milton had a highly <qex>imaginative</qex>, Cowley a very fanciful
mind.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Unreasonably suspicious; jealous.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Im*ag"i*na*tive*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Im*ag"i*na*tive*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>imaginativeness</ent>⟦br⟧
